Critics have blamed a string of 
suicides and injuries on appalling conditions at the 'sweatshop 
factories', where 90 per cent of Apple's products are put together.

As a result of the report, Apple and 
Foxconn bosses have agreed to reduce working hours, improve health and 
safety conditions, and 'establish a genuine voice for the workers'.

Apple said in a statement: 'Empowering workers and helping them understand their rights is essential.'

The investigation found that within 
the past year, all three factories exceeded both the group's standard of
60 working hours a week and 36 hours maximum overtime a month. Some 
also exceeded the work week limit of 76 hours set by Chinese law.

