It came as Apple chief Tim Cook paid a
visit to China. Vice premier Li Keqiang, who is likely to be the 
country's next leader, reportedly told Mr Cook that multinational 
companies should 'pay more attention to caring for workers'.

However, 
the report has not been favourably received by some of the factories' 
workers, many of whom are concerned that a cut in hours will mean much 
lower salaries.

One employee, a 23-year-old called Wu,
said: 'We are worried we'll have less money. If we work less overtime, 
it means less money.' Apple stocks fell slightly after the report's 
findings were unveiled.

Foxconn City is part of Taiwan's Hon 
Hai Precision Industry Company, which employs up to 1.1million in 
factory complexes in China.

The New York Times claimed in a recent
report that some workers making iPads and iPhones said they stand so 
long their legs swell until they can hardly walk.

Between 2009 and 2011, at least 19 
Foxconn staff were linked to suicides or attempted suicides. Foxconn – 
which also makes items for Sony, Nintendo and Hewlett Packard – disputed
claims of long shifts and crowded living conditions.

